# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ais-kacang
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ais-kacang/acar] Through examining the etymology, the similar sounding name strongly suggests that indeed acar was derived from the Indian achar pickle.
[src:ais-kacang/acar] Indian achar was transmitted in antiquity to the maritime realm of Southeast Asia, which today is recognized as acar in Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore and Brunei, and then on to the Philippines as *atchara*.
[src:ais-kacang/acar] The adoption of this vegetable pickling technique possibly took place during the Srivijaya period between 7th to 13th century.
[src:ais-kacang/acar] British navigator Thomas Forrest wrote that acar made of salted limes and palm vinegar was often of use to Coromandel Muslim sailors (*Chulias*) to prevent scurvy and was sold as far as Aceh.
[src:ais-kacang/acar] The Southeast Asian variations are usually made from different vegetables such as cucumber, carrots, cabbage, shallot, bird's eye chili and yardlong beans, which are pickled in vinegar, sometimes with kaffir lime to add citrus aroma, and also dried chillies.
[src:ais-kacang/acar] Some recipes might have the vegetables tossed in ground peanuts.
[src:ais-kacang/acar] *Acar* is commonly served as a condiment to be eaten with a main course, such as *martabak*, *nasi goreng* (fried rice), satay, and almost all varieties of *soto*.
[src:ais-kacang/acar] Just like common pickles, the sour taste of *acar* is meant to freshen up a meal, especially fishy dishes such as *ikan bakar* (grilled fish) or rich and oily dishes such as mutton satay to neutralize the fat.
[src:ais-kacang/acar] In Indonesia, acar is commonly made from small chunks of cucumber, carrot, shallot, bird's eye chili and occasionally pineapple, and marinated in a sweet and sour solution of sugar and vinegar.
[src:ais-kacang/acar] Some households add lemongrass or ginger to spice it up.
[src:ais-kacang/acar] It is usually used as condiment to accompany grilled foods such as satay.
[src:ais-kacang/acar] Nevertheless, *acar* can also be consumed as a whole, complete dish.
[src:ais-kacang/acar] For example, *ikan acar kuning* is a fish dish (gourami, mackerel or tilapia) served in *acar* pickles of cucumber, carrot, shallot and red chili, mixed with yellow spice paste made of ground turmeric, candlenut, ginger, garlic and shallot.
[src:ais-kacang/acar] It is known as *atjar* (pickle) in Dutch cuisine, derived from Indonesian *acar*, since the Netherlands and Indonesia share colonial ties.
[src:ais-kacang/acar] Variations of Malaysian and Singaporean *acar* include *acar awak* or Nyonya *acar* and Malay *acar*.
[src:ais-kacang/acar] *Acar awak* is more elaborate, containing additional vegetables such as eggplants as well as aromatic spices in the pickling mix.
[src:ais-kacang/acar] The salad has also been adopted into Thai cuisine, where it is called *achat* (Thai: อาจาด, pronounced [ʔāː.t͡ɕàːt]).
[src:ais-kacang/acar] It is made with cucumber, red chilies, red onions or shallots, vinegar, sugar and salt.
[src:ais-kacang/acar] It is served as a side dish with the Thai version of satay (Thai: สะเต๊ะ).
[src:ais-kacang/acar] With Indian and Malay slaves initially brought by the British Empire, *atchar* became a favourite condiment in South Africa.
[src:ais-kacang/acar] The local variation is usually made with green mangoes.
[src:ais-kacang/adhirasam] Adhirasam is a popular as an offering to the relatives during Deepavali and Ganesha Chaturthi festivals, both at home and in temples in Tamil Nadu and Karnataka.
[src:ais-kacang/adhirasam] The earliest documented references to Adhirasam emerge from medieval Tamil kingdoms, particularly the Chola dynasty, where it appeared as a favored item in royal feasts and temple rituals.
[src:ais-kacang/adhirasam] According to inscriptions from the 16th century, during the reign of Vijayanagara emperor Krishnadevaraya, the sweet was made from rice flour, jaggery, ghee and pepper.
[src:ais-kacang/adhirasam] At the annual festival at the Panchavarnesvar Temple in Thirunallur (located near Kumbakonam, Tamil Nadu), an offering of 6000 Adhirasams along with 6000 vadas is made to the Gods; the entire lot is cooked in the temple kitchen between sunrise and 11 pm, for the prayers that take place at midnight.
[src:ais-kacang/adhirasam] It is a popular Deepavali sweet preparation for Tamil people.
[src:ais-kacang/adhirasam] The authentic preparation takes about a week.
[src:ais-kacang/adhirasam] First the rice is soaked in water and dried in shade and ground into a fine powder when the rice is 3/4th dried and retains some moisture.
[src:ais-kacang/adhirasam] For adding sweet "vellam" (jaggery in Tamil) is melted in water by boiling it till it reaches soft-ball consistency (235–240 °F (113–116 °C), if using a candy thermometer) and added to the rice flour along with some powdered cardamom to make a thick dough.
[src:ais-kacang/adhirasam] It is then transferred to an earthenware pot and the top of the pot is closed with a thin white cloth.
[src:ais-kacang/adhirasam] It is then allowed to ferment for about 3–5 days by placing it in the sunlight during the day.
[src:ais-kacang/adhirasam] Finally, when the batter is ready for preparation, small balls of the dough is taken and flattened using fingers in a small piece of oil-brushed banana leaf and deep fried in oil until golden brown.
[src:ais-kacang/adhirasam] Then it is pressed with a flat bottomed bowl to remove the excess oil.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Scientists presume *Vigna angularis* var.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] The description of the adzuki bean can vary between authors because there are both wild and cultivated forms of the plant.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] The adzuki bean is an annual, rarely biennial bushy erect or twining herb usually between 30 and 90 centimetres (12 and 35 in) high.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] There exist climbing or prostrate forms of the plant.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] The stem is normally green and sparsely pilose.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] The adzuki bean has a taproot type of root system that can reach a depth of 40–50 centimetres (16–20 in) from the point of seed germination.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] The leaves of the adzuki bean are trifoliate, pinnate and arranged alternately along the stem on a long petiole.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Leaflets are ovate and about 5–10 centimetres (2.0–3.9 in) long and 5–8 centimetres (2.0–3.1 in) wide.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Adzuki flowers are papilionaceous and bright yellow.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] The inflorescence is an axillary false raceme consisting of six to ten (two to twenty) flowers.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Adzuki pods are smooth, cylindrical, and thin walled.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] The colour of the pods is green turning white to grey as they mature.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Pod shatter during seed ripening, and harvesting can be difficult under certain conditions.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] The thousand kernel weight is between 50 and 200 g.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] There are many different seed colours from maroon to blue-black mottled with straw.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] The emergence of the seedlings is hypogeal and takes 7–20 days.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Compared to other pulses the growth of the plant is slow.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Normally the adzuki plant reaches maturity between 80 and 120 days depending on the cultivar and the environmental conditions.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Commonly the plant self-pollinates but cross-pollination also exists.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] The wild ancestor of cultivated adzuki bean is probably *Vigna angularis* var.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] *nipponensis*, which is distributed across East Asia.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Speciation between *Vigna angularis* var.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] *nipponensis* and *Vigna angularis* var.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] *angularis* occurred around 50,000 years ago.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Wild adzuki likely originated near the Himalayas and spread naturally to central China and Japan.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Archaeologists estimate it was domesticated around 3000 BC.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] However, adzuki beans, as well as soybeans, dating from 3000 BC to 2000 BC are indicated to still be largely within the wild size range.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Enlarged seeds occurred during the later Bronze Age or Iron Age, periods with plough use.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Domestication of adzuki beans resulted in a trade-off between yield and seed size.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Cultivated adzuki beans have fewer but longer pods, fewer but larger seeds, a shorter stature, and also a smaller overall seed yield than wild forms.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] The exact place of domestication is not known; multiple domestication origins in East Asia have been suggested.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Seed remains of adzuki beans discovered in the Central Highlands of Japan were dated to c.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] 6,000–4,000 BP, and represent to date the oldest evidence for its cultivation, supporting an origin in Japan.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Evidence suggests that "wild azuki bean have been domesticated and cultivated in Japan for over 10,000 years".
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] While archaeological studies found early traces of adzuki cultivation in Japan, genetic studies identified highest cultivar genetic variation in central China, suggesting the first domestication in China.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Cultivated azuki beans have been found in Shandong, dated to the 9th millennium BC.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Consistent with archaeological records, a genomic study indicated that all present-day adzuki cultivars descended from the wild adzuki in eastern Japan near the Central Highlands, at about 3000-5000 BP.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] The cultivars later spread to China and hybridized with local wild adzuki in China, resulting in the high genetic variation of central Chinese cultivars.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] The study therefore reconciles the discrepancy between archaeological and early genetic studies.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Mutations conferring key domestication syndromes (loss of pod shattering and change of seed coat color) also had a single origin in Japan.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] These mutations originated and continued to increase in frequency since about 10,000 BP, suggesting that domestication syndromes were being selected by the Jōmon people much earlier than clear archaeological traces of large-scale cultivation.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] In Japan, the adzuki bean was one of the first crops subjected to scientific plant breeding.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Important breeding traits are yield, pureness of the bean colour, and the maturing time.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Separate cultivars with smaller seeds and higher biomass are bred for fodder production and as green manure.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Locally adapted cultivars are available in China, Japan, Korea, and Taiwan.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] More than 300 cultivars/landraces/breeding lines are registered in Japan.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Large germplasm collections of adzuki bean are in China, at the Institute of Crop Germplasm Resources (CAAS), Beijing, with more than 3,700 accessions, and Japan, at the Tokachi Agricultural Experiment Station, Hokkaido, with about 2,500 accessions.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Weed forms of adzuki bean frequently occur in Japan.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] The wide spread of weed forms is due to adaptation to human-disturbed habitats, escapes of old cultivars, and natural establishment from derivatives of hybrids between cultivars and wild forms.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] In contrast to wild forms, the weed forms of adzuki bean are used as a substitute for the cultivated form and consumed as sweet beans, especially if cultivated adzuki beans are attacked by pests.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] However, in cultivated gardens the weed form is recognized as contamination and lowers the seed quality of adzuki cultivars.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] The name *adzuki* is a transliteration of the Japanese アヅキ, as it was spelled according to historical kana orthography.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] The names *azuki* and *aduki* reflect the modern pronunciation アズキ (hiragana: あずき).
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] All are meant to represent the same Modern Japanese pronunciation, *azuki*.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Japanese also has a Chinese loanword, *shōzu* (小豆), which means "small bean", its counterpart "large bean" (大豆, **daizu**) being the soybean.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] It is common to write 小豆 in kanji but pronounce it as *azuki* *listenⓘ*, an example of **jukujikun**.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] In China, the corresponding name (Chinese: 小豆; pinyin: *xiǎodòu*) still is used in botanical or agricultural parlance.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] In everyday Chinese, the more common terms are **hongdou** (红豆; 紅豆; *hóngdòu*) and **chidou** (赤豆; *chìdòu*), both meaning "**red bean**", because almost all Chinese cultivars are uniformly red.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] In English the beans are often described as "red beans" in the context of Chinese cuisine, such as with red bean paste.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] In Korean, adzuki beans are called **pat** (팥) and it contrasts with **kong** (콩, "bean"), rather than being considered a type of it.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] **Kong** ("beans") without qualifiers usually means soybeans.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] In Vietnamese it is called **đậu đỏ** (literally: red bean).
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] In some parts of India, the beans are referred to as "red chori".
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] In Marathi, it is known as **lal chavali** (लाल चवळी), literally meaning 'red cowpea'.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] In Iraq its name is **lūbyā ḥamrāˈ** (لوبيا حمراء) meaning "red cowpeas".
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] The bean is also grown commercially in the US, South America, India, New Zealand, Congo, and Angola.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] In Japan, the adzuki bean is the second most important legume after the soy bean.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Japan is the largest importer of adzuki beans.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] The imports come from China, Korea, Colombia, Taiwan, the US, Thailand, and Canada.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Optimal temperature range for adzuki bean growth is between 15 and 30 °C (59 and 86 °F).
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] The crop is not frost-hardy and needs soil temperatures above 6–10 °C (43–50 °F) (30–34 °C (86–93 °F) optimal) for germination.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Hot temperatures stimulate vegetative growth and are therefore less favorable for pea production.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] The adzuki bean is usually not irrigated.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Annual rainfall ranges from 500 to 1,750 millimetres (20 to 69 in) in areas where the bean is grown.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] The plant can withstand drought but severe reduction in yield is expected.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] The cultivation of the adzuki bean is possible on preferably well drained soils with pH 5–7.5.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Fertilizer application differs widely depending on expected yield but is generally similar to soybean.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Due to nodulation with rhizobia, nitrogen fixation of up to 100 kilograms per hectare (89 lb/acre) is possible.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] The sowing of the peas is in 2–3 centimetres (0.79–1.18 in) depth in rows 30–90 centimetres (12–35 in) apart and 10–45 centimetres (3.9–17.7 in) within the row.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] The amount of seeds ranges between 8–70 kilograms per hectare (7.1–62.5 lb/acre).
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Growth of the crop is slow, therefore weed control is crucial mainly between germination and flowering.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Cultivation systems differ largely among different countries.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] In China adzuki bean is often grown in intercrops with maize, sorghum and millet while in Japan the bean is grown in crop rotations.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Harvest of the peas should not be done as long as moisture content of the seed is higher than 16%.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Fungal and bacterial diseases of the adzuki bean are powdery mildew, brown stem rot, and bacterial blight.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Furthermore, pests such as the adzuki pod worm, Japanese butterbur borer, and cutworm attack the crop.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] The bean weevil is an important storage pest.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] In East Asian cuisine, adzuki beans are most commonly sweetened before eating.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] They are often boiled with sugar to produce red bean paste, a widely used ingredient throughout the region.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] The paste is sometimes flavored with ingredients such as chestnut and serves as a filling or topping in numerous traditional dishes.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] In Chinese cuisine, red bean paste appears in foods such as tangyuan, zongzi, mooncakes, baozi, and red bean ice.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] A more liquid preparation, made by boiling adzuki beans with sugar and a pinch of salt, is known as hong dou tang, a sweet soup-like dessert.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] In Japanese cuisine, red bean paste is used in confections including anpan, dorayaki, imagawayaki, manjū, monaka, anmitsu, taiyaki, and daifuku.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] It is also used in amanattō and in ice cream, either as whole beans or as a paste.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Rice with adzuki beans (赤飯; *sekihan*) is traditionally prepared in Japan for auspicious occasions.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Across East Asia, red bean paste and adzuki beans are also enjoyed in waffles, pastries, baked buns, spring rolls, and biscuits.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] In addition, adzuki beans may be eaten sprouted or boiled in a hot, tea-like drink.
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] Cooked adzuki beans are 66% water, 25% carbohydrates, including 7% dietary fiber, 8% protein, and contain negligible fat (table).
[src:ais-kacang/adzuki-bean] In a 100-gram reference amount, cooked beans provide 536 kilojoules (128 kilocalories) of food energy, a moderate to high content (10% or more of the Daily Value, DV) of the B vitamin folate (30% DV), and several dietary minerals (11% to 27% DV, table).
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] As found in nature, agar is a mixture of two components, the linear polysaccharide agarose and a heterogeneous mixture of smaller molecules called agaropectin.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] It forms the supporting structure in the cell walls of certain species of algae, and is released on boiling.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] The processing of food-grade agar removes the agaropectin, and the commercial product is essentially pure agarose.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Agar has been used as an ingredient in desserts throughout Asia and also as a solid substrate to contain culture media for microbiological work.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Agar can be used as a laxative; an appetite suppressant; a vegan substitute for gelatin; a thickener for soups; in fruit preserves, ice cream, and other desserts; as a clarifying agent in brewing; and for sizing paper and fabrics.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] The word *agar* comes from **agar-agar**, the Malay name for red algae (*Gigartina*, *Eucheuma*, *Gracilaria*) from which the jelly is produced.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] It is also known as **kanten** (Japanese: 寒天) (from the phrase ***kan**-zarashi tokoro**ten*** (寒晒し心太) or "cold-exposed agar"), **Japanese isinglass**, **China grass**, **Ceylon moss**, and **Jaffna moss**.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] *Gracilaria edulis* or its synonym *G. lichenoides* is specifically referred to as **agal-agal** or **Ceylon agar**.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Macroalgae have been used widely as food by coastal cultures, especially in Southeast Asia.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] In the Philippines, *Gracilaria*, known as *gulaman* (also *guraman*, *gar-garao*, or *gulaman dagat*, among other names) in Tagalog, have been harvested and used as food for centuries, eaten both fresh or sun-dried and turned into jellies.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Carrageenan, derived from gusô (*Eucheuma* spp.), which also congeals into a gel-like texture is also used similarly among the Visayan peoples and have been recorded in the even earlier *Diccionario De La Lengua Bisaya, Hiligueina y Haraia de la isla de Panay y Sugbu y para las demas islas* (c.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] 1637) of the Augustinian missionary Alonso de Méntrida (in Spanish).
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] In the book, Méntrida describes gusô as being cooked until it melts, and then allowed to congeal into a sour dish.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] In Ambon Island in the Maluku Islands of Indonesia, agar is extracted from *Graciliaria* and eaten as a type of pickle or a sauce.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Jelly seaweeds were also favoured and foraged by Malay communities living on the coasts of the Riau Archipelago and Singapore in Southeast Asia for centuries.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] 19th century records indicate that dried *Graciliaria* were one of the bulk exports of British Malaya to China.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Poultices made from agar were also used for swollen knee joints and sores in Johore and Singapore.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Agar normally solidifies at room temperature without the need to freeze.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Agar was first subjected to chemical analysis in 1859 by the French chemist Anselme Payen, who had obtained agar from the marine algae *Gelidium corneum*.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Beginning in the late 19th century, agar began to be used as a solid medium for growing various microbes.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Agar was first described for use in microbiology in 1882 by the German microbiologist Walther Hesse, an assistant working in Robert Koch's laboratory, on the suggestion of his wife Fanny Hesse.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Agar quickly supplanted gelatin as the base of microbiological media, due to its higher melting temperature, allowing microbes to be grown at higher temperatures without the media liquefying.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] With its newfound use in microbiology, agar production quickly increased.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] This production centered on Japan, which produced most of the world's agar until World War II.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] However, with the outbreak of World War II, many nations were forced to establish domestic agar industries in order to continue microbiological research.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Around the time of World War II, approximately 2,500 tons of agar were produced annually.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] By the mid-1970s, production worldwide had increased dramatically to approximately 10,000 tons each year.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Since then, production of agar has fluctuated due to unstable and sometimes over-utilized seaweed populations.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Agar consists of a mixture of two polysaccharides: agarose and agaropectin.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Agarose constitutes about 70% of the mixture, while agaropectin constitutes about 30% of it.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Agarose is a linear polymer made up of repeating units of agarobiose, a disaccharide made up of D-galactose and 3,6-anhydro-L-galactopyranose.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Agaropectin is a heterogeneous mixture of smaller molecules that occur in lesser amounts, and is made up of alternating units of D-galactose and L-galactose heavily modified with acidic side-groups, such as sulfate, glucuronate, and pyruvate.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Agar exhibits a phenomenon known as hysteresis whereby, when mixed with water, it solidifies and forms a gel below about 32–42 °C (305–315 K; 90–108 °F), which is called the gel point, and melts above 85 °C (358 K; 185 °F), which is the melting point.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Hysteresis is the property of having a difference between the gel point and melting point temperatures.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] This property lends a suitable balance between easy melting and good gel stability at relatively high temperatures.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Since many scientific applications require incubation at temperatures close to human body temperature (37 °C), agar is more appropriate than other solidifying agents that melt at this temperature, such as gelatin.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Agar-agar is a natural vegetable gelatin counterpart.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] It is white and semi-translucent when sold in packages as washed and dried strips or in powdered form.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] It can be used to make jellies, puddings, and custards.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] When making jelly, it is boiled in water until the solids dissolve.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Sweetener, flavoring, coloring, fruits and or vegetables are then added, and the liquid is poured into molds to be served as desserts and vegetable aspics or incorporated with other desserts such as a layer of jelly in a cake.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Agar-agar is approximately 80% dietary fiber, so it can serve as an intestinal regulator.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Its bulking quality has been behind fad diets in Asia, for example the *kanten* (the Japanese word for agar-agar) diet.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Once ingested, *kanten* triples in size and absorbs water.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] This results in the consumers feeling fuller.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] One use of agar in Japanese cuisine is in *anmitsu*, a dessert made of small cubes of agar jelly and served in a bowl with various fruits or other ingredients.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] It is also the main ingredient in *mizu yōkan*, another popular Japanese food.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] In Philippine cuisine, it is used to make the jelly bars in the various gulaman refreshments like *sago't gulaman*, *samalamig*, or desserts such as *buko pandan*, *agar flan*, *halo-halo*, *fruit cocktail jelly*, and the black and red *gulaman* used in various fruit salads.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] In Vietnamese cuisine, jellies made of flavored layers of agar-agar, called *thạch*, are a popular dessert, and are often made in ornate molds for special occasions.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] In Indian cuisine, agar is used for making desserts.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] In Burmese cuisine, a sweet jelly known as *kyauk kyaw* is made from agar.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Agar jelly is widely used in Taiwanese bubble tea.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] It can be used as addition to (or as a replacement for) pectin in jelly, jam, or marmalade, as a substitute to gelatin for its superior gelling properties, and as a strengthening ingredient in souffles and custards.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Another use of agar-agar is in a Russian dish *ptich'ye moloko* (bird's milk), a rich jellified custard (or soft meringue) used as a cake filling or chocolate-glazed as individual sweets.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Agar-agar may also be used as the gelling agent in gel clarification, a culinary technique used to clarify stocks, sauces, and other liquids.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Mexico has traditional candies made out of Agar gelatin, most of them in colorful, half-circle shapes that resemble a melon or watermelon fruit slice, and commonly covered with sugar.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Agar-agar is an allowed nonorganic/nonsynthetic additive used as a thickener, gelling agent, texturizer, moisturizer, emulsifier, flavor enhancer, and absorbent in certified organic foods.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] An agar plate or Petri dish is used to provide a growth medium using a mix of agar and other nutrients in which microorganisms, including bacteria and fungi, can be cultured and observed under the microscope.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Agar is indigestible for many organisms so that microbial growth does not affect the gel used and it remains stable.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Agar is typically sold commercially as a powder that can be mixed with water and prepared similarly to gelatin before use as a growth medium.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Nutrients are typically added to meet the nutritional needs of the microbes organism, the formulations of which may be "undefined" where the precise composition is unknown, or "defined" where the exact chemical composition is known.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Agar is often dispensed using a sterile media dispenser.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Different algae produce various types of agar.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Each agar has unique properties that suit different purposes.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Because of the agarose component, the agar solidifies.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] When heated, agarose has the potential to melt and then solidify.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Because of this property, they are referred to as "physical gels".
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] In contrast, polyacrylamide polymerization is an irreversible process, and the resulting products are known as chemical gels.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] There are a variety of different types of agar that support the growth of different microorganisms.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] A nutrient agar may be permissive, allowing for the cultivation of any non-fastidious microorganisms; a commonly used nutrient agar for bacteria is the Luria Bertani (LB) agar which contains lysogeny broth, a nutrient-rich medium used for bacterial growth.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Additionally, 2216 Marine Broth (MB) agar, with high salt content, is optimized for growing heterotrophic marine bacteria like those of the *Vibrio* genus, while Terrific Broth (TB) agar is used to non-selectively culture high yields of the bacterium *E. coli*.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] More generally, enriched media is an agar variety that is infused with the necessary nutrients required by fastidious organisms to grow.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Despite the large diversity of agar mediums, yeast extract is a common ingredient across all varieties as it is a macronutrient that provides a nitrogen source for all bacterial cell types.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Other fastidious organisms may require the addition of different biological fluids such as horse or sheep blood, serum, egg yolk, and so on.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Agar plates can also be selective, and can be used to promote the growth of bacteria of interest while inhibiting others.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] A variety of chemicals may be added to create an environment favourable for specific types of bacteria or bacteria with certain properties, but not conducive for growth of others.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] For example, antibiotics may be added in cloning experiments whereby bacteria with antibiotic-resistant plasmid are selected.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] In addition to antibiotic treated agar, other selective and indicator agar plates include TCBS agar and MacConkey agar.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Thiosulfate citrate bile salts sucrose (TCBS) agar is used to differentiate Vibrio species based on their sucrose metabolism, since only some will metabolize the sucrose in the plate and change its pH.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Indicator dyes included in the gel will display a visual change of the pH by changing the gel color from green to yellow.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] MacConkey agar contains bile salts and crystal violet to selectively grow gram-negative bacteria and differentiate between species using pH-indicator dyes that demonstrate lactose metabolism properties.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] As a gel, an agar or agarose medium is porous and therefore can be used to measure microorganism motility and mobility.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] The gel's porosity is directly related to the concentration of agarose in the medium, so various levels of effective viscosity (from the cell's "point of view") can be selected, depending on the experimental objectives.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] A common identification assay involves culturing a sample of the organism deep within a block of nutrient agar.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Cells will attempt to grow within the gel structure.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Motile species will be able to migrate, albeit slowly, throughout the gel, and infiltration rates can then be visualized, whereas non-motile species will show growth only along the now-empty path introduced by the invasive initial sample deposition.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Another setup commonly used for measuring chemotaxis and chemokinesis utilizes the under-agarose cell migration assay, whereby a layer of agarose gel is placed between a cell population and a chemoattractant.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] As a concentration gradient develops from the diffusion of the chemoattractant into the gel, various cell populations requiring different stimulation levels to migrate can then be visualized over time using microphotography as they tunnel upward through the gel against gravity along the gradient.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Research grade agar is used extensively in plant biology as it is optionally supplemented with a nutrient and/or vitamin mixture that allows for seedling germination in Petri dishes under sterile conditions (given that the seeds are sterilized as well).
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Nutrient and/or vitamin supplementation for *Arabidopsis thaliana* is standard across most experimental conditions.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Murashige & Skoog (MS) nutrient mix and Gamborg's B5 vitamin mix in general are used.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] A 1.0% agar/0.44% MS+vitamin dH2O solution is suitable for growth media between normal growth temps.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] When using agar, within any growth medium, it is important to know that the solidification of the agar is pH-dependent.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] The optimal range for solidification is between 5.4 and 5.7.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Usually, the application of potassium hydroxide is needed to increase the pH to this range.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] A general guideline is about 600 μl 0.1M KOH per 250 ml GM.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] This entire mixture can be sterilized using the liquid cycle of an autoclave.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] This hormone/GM solution can be spread across the surface of Petri dishes sown with germinated and/or etiolated seedlings.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Experiments with the moss *Physcomitrella patens*, however, have shown that choice of the gelling agent – agar or Gelrite – does influence phytohormone sensitivity of the plant cell culture.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Gelidium agar is used primarily for bacteriological plates.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] Gracilaria agar is used mainly in food applications.
[src:ais-kacang/agar-agar] In 2016, AMAM, a Japanese company, developed a prototype for agar-based commercial packaging system called Agar Plasticity, intended as a replacement for oil-based plastic packaging.
[src:ais-kacang/ais-kacang] Traditionally, an ice shaving machine is used to churn out the shaved ice used in the dessert, originally hand cranked but now more often motorised.
[src:ais-kacang/ais-kacang] Many Southeast Asian coffee shops, hawker centres and food courts sell this dessert.
[src:ais-kacang/ais-kacang] Early versions of ais kacang was first known to have been prepared around the time before and after the First World War, where the costs of ice manufacturing was becoming more affordable.
[src:ais-kacang/ais-kacang] An earlier variant of the Singaporean dish was described as green, made from shaved ice, paired with syrups, *soaked seeds* and seaweed jelly and was sold mainly by street vendors.
[src:ais-kacang/ais-kacang] The dish underwent many different alterations and variants throughout the history of Singapore, where during the 1920s, one version of it was described as shaved ice topped with rose water, lime or liquorice.
[src:ais-kacang/ais-kacang] A version of the dish, known as Kachang mera, was also sold during the 1930s.
[src:ais-kacang/ais-kacang] By the 1940s, the version of the dish described as having "shaved ice heaped into a little mountain", topped with red beans, "a Chinese grape-like fruit", syrup, and condensed or evaporated milk, similar to how it is being prepared today, began to appear.
[src:ais-kacang/ais-kacang] Some earlier variants of ais kacang are no longer sold, such as the ice ball version of the dessert, which was popular during the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:ais-kacang/ais-kacang] In Malaysia, variants now contain a large serving of *attap chee* (palm seed), red beans, sweet corn, grass jelly, roasted peanuts, and cubes of agar agar as common ingredients.
[src:ais-kacang/ais-kacang] Other less common ingredients include aloe vera, *cendol*, *nata de coco*, and ice cream.
[src:ais-kacang/ais-kacang] A final topping of evaporated milk, condensed milk, or coconut milk is drizzled over the mountain of ice along with red rose syrup and sarsi syrup.
[src:ais-kacang/ais-kacang] Some stalls have even introduced novelty toppings such as durian and chocolate syrup.
[src:ais-kacang/ais-kacang] There are also versions that shun the multi-coloured syrup and are served instead with just a drizzling of palm sugar syrup.
[src:ais-kacang/ais-kacang] In Singapore, traditional ice kachang is usually made from shaved ice, packed into a mountain-like shape and consists of red beans, creamed corn, attap chee, cendol, and grass jelly, similar to the Malaysian version, and drizzled with syrups made from gula melaka, red rose syrup, and pandan syrup.
[src:ais-kacang/ais-kacang] The dish has evolved to include fruits such as durian, mango, toppings such as Milo, peanuts, and sago pearls among others.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] Based on a report released by International Organisation of Good Templars in 2016, Malaysia has the third highest tax on alcohol worldwide at 15%, behind Norway and Singapore which are predicted to keep increasing.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] The country has an annual spending of RM2 billion on alcoholic drinks.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] Prior to the Trans-Pacific Partnership, Malaysia together with Vietnam plans to drop import tariffs on beer, whisky, and other alcoholic drinks.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] The tradition of brewing alcoholic drinks in Malaysia is most prominent in the island of Borneo.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] Indigenous islanders traditionally drank home-made rice wine called tuak and tapai in their communal gatherings and harvest festivals of Gawai Dayak and Kaamatan.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] Alcohol consumption in the Malay Peninsula has been less common since the introduction of Islam.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] However, the production and consumption of alcohol (*arak*) has been a tradition since the time of Hang Tuah in the 15th century.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] In the 20th century, palm toddy was popular among the local Indian and Chinese communities.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] The British brought their own traditional brewed alcoholic drinks, such as beer and stout.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] In the 1930, the first brewery was established in neighbouring British Singapore.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] Since the British colonial times, Tiger Beer was the first commercial beer brewed in 1932 by Malayan Breweries Limited, a Singapore-based brewery which was formed from a merger between Heineken and Fraser and Neave (F&N).
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] The beginning of alcohol production in Malaysia started in 1968, when two leading breweries, Guinness and Malayan, merged to form a new company known as Guinness Anchor Berhad.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] In 1970, Carlsberg established its first brewery outside Kuala Lumpur in Shah Alam.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] Both are since the only legal commercial breweries in Malaysia, which account for 95% of the total beer and stout volume in the country market.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] In 2007, another two breweries known as Napex and Jaz brewed beer for pubs in the country, but both have since ceased from operation.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] Beside local productions, many alcoholic drinks in the country are also imported from neighbouring countries such as Singapore, Thailand, Indonesia, Philippines and Vietnam.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] The legal drinking age (purchasing) for Malaysia is 21 years old and above.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] Since 2020, the legal limit for blood alcohol level while driving in Malaysia is 50 mg per 100 ml for blood test; 22 μg per 100 ml for breath test; and 67 mg per 100 ml for urine test.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] Public drinking or public intoxication is not a crime in Malaysia, unless the drunken person caused "annoyance" towards others or exhibit "disorderly behaviour", which may be punished with a RM20 to RM25 fine or a 10 to 14 days jail under the Penal Code or Minor Offences Act 1955.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] However, these laws are rarely enforced.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] Any vendors, restaurants and retailers need a licence to serve or sell tap/draft beers, liquor and spirits in the country.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] Bottled and canned beers are exempted from such licence requirements, which is why it is common to find many vendors and coffee houses serving alcohol in their premises without a licence.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] Malaysia also imposes nationwide regulations for vendors to place their alcoholic drinks into separate refrigerators or storage places, although this was opposed by certain vendors in the state of Penang.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] The high tax on alcohol has increased the price of alcoholic drinks in Malaysia, harming some drinkers who turn to unsafe alcohol smuggled in from neighbouring countries.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] In 2018, around 45 people died in the country's worst methanol poisoning involving foreign workers and several Malaysians due to the consumption of cheap fake liquors acquired from the country's black markets.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] Following Demerit Points System for Traffic Offences (KEJARA), a police officer or JPJ officer can take breath, blood or urine samples of drunk driver.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] If alcohol content is found in the samples, a fine of RM 2000 or 6 months' imprisonment may be imposed for the first offence.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] Alcohol is generally prohibited for Muslim consumers in the country as Malaysia's sharia law forbids Muslims from drinking alcohol.
[src:ais-kacang/alcohol-in-malaysia] Alcohol is mostly banned for Muslims in the states of Kelantan and Terengganu.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] An evergreen perennial, it originates from the Arabian Peninsula, but also grows wild in tropical, semi-tropical, and arid climates around the world.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] It is cultivated commercially and has been used for centuries as a topical treatment.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] The species is considered attractive for decorative purposes, and is often used indoors as a potted plant.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] The leaves of *Aloe vera* contain significant amounts of the polysaccharide gel acemannan, which may be used for topical purposes.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] The leaves also contain aloin, which is a toxic compound.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] *Aloe vera* products are typically made from the gel.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] Oral ingestion of aloe vera extracts may cause acute abdominal pain and cramps, and hepatitis if consumed chronically.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] Some people have allergic reactions to aloe when used on skin.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] The genus name *Aloe* is derived from the Arabic word *alloeh*, meaning "bitter and shiny substance" or from Hebrew אוהלים *ahalim*, plural of אוהל *ahal*.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] The specific epithet *vera* comes from *verus* meaning "true" in Latin.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] Common names use *aloe* with a region of its distribution, such as *Chinese aloe*, *Cape aloe* or *Barbados aloe*.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] The species has several synonyms: *Aloe barbadensis* Mill., *Aloe indica* Royle, *Aloe perfoliata* L. var.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] Some literature identifies the white-spotted form of *Aloe vera* as *Aloe vera* var.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] *chinensis*; and the spotted form of *Aloe vera* may be conspecific with *A. massawana*.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] The species was first described by Carl Linnaeus in 1753 as *Aloe perfoliata* var.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] *vera*, and was described again in 1768 by Nicolaas Laurens Burman as *Aloe vera* in *Flora Indica* on 6 April and by Philip Miller as *Aloe barbadensis* some ten days after Burman in the *Gardener's Dictionary*.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] Techniques based on DNA comparison suggest *Aloe vera* is relatively closely related to *Aloe perryi*, a species endemic to Yemen.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] Similar techniques, using chloroplast DNA sequence comparison and inter simple sequence repeat profiling have also suggested it is closely related to *Aloe forbesii*, *Aloe inermis*, *Aloe scobinifolia*, *Aloe sinkatana*, and *Aloe striata*.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] With the exception of the South African species *A. striata*, these *Aloe* species are native to Socotra (Yemen), Somalia, and Sudan.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] The lack of obvious natural populations of the species has led some authors to suggest *Aloe vera* may be of hybrid origin.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] The leaves are thick and fleshy, green to grey-green, with some varieties showing white flecks on their upper and lower stem surfaces.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] The margin of the leaf is serrated and has small white teeth.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] The flowers are produced in summer on a spike up to 90 cm (35 in) tall, each flower being pendulous, with a yellow tubular corolla 2–3 cm (3⁄4–1+1⁄4 in) long.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] Like other *Aloe* species, *Aloe vera* forms arbuscular mycorrhiza, a root symbiosis that allows the plant better access to mineral nutrients from the soil.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] The species was introduced to China and various parts of southern Europe in the 17th century.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] It is widely naturalized elsewhere, occurring in arid, temperate, and tropical regions of temperate continents.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] The current distribution may be the result of cultivation.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] In pots, the species requires well-drained, sandy potting soil, and bright, sunny conditions.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] Aloe plants can turn red from sunburn under too much direct sun, though gradual acclimation may help.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] The use of a good-quality commercial propagation mix or packaged "cacti and succulent mix" is recommended, as they allow good drainage.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] Terra cotta pots are preferable as they are porous.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] Potted plants should be allowed to completely dry before rewatering.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] When potted, aloes can become crowded with "pups" growing from the sides of the "mother plant".
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] Plants that have become crowded can be divided and repotted to allow room for further growth, or the pups can be left with the mother plant.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] During winter, *Aloe vera* may become dormant, during which little moisture is required.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] In areas that receive frost or snow, the species is best kept indoors or in heated glasshouses.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] There is large-scale agricultural production of *Aloe vera* in Australia, Cuba, the Dominican Republic, China, Mexico, India, Jamaica, Kenya, Tanzania, South Africa, Spain, and the United States, with much of the output going toward the cosmetics industry.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] Two substances from *Aloe vera* – a clear gel and its yellow latex – are used to manufacture commercial products.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] Aloe gel typically is used to make topical medications for skin conditions, such as burns, wounds, frostbite, rashes, psoriasis, cold sores, and dry skin.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] Aloe latex is used individually or manufactured as a product with other ingredients to be ingested for relief of constipation.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] Aloe latex may be obtained in a dried form called *resin* or as "aloe dried juice".
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] There is conflicting evidence regarding whether *Aloe vera* is effective as a treatment for wounds or burns.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] Topical use of aloe products may relieve symptoms of certain skin disorders, such as psoriasis, acne, or rashes, but may also cause an allergic reaction in some people.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] For people with allergies to *Aloe vera*, skin reactions may include contact dermatitis with mild redness and itching, difficulty with breathing, or swelling of the face, lips, tongue, or throat.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] Orally ingested non-decolorized aloe vera leaf extract was listed by the California Office of Environmental Health Hazard Assessment among "chemicals known to the state to cause cancer or reproductive toxicity", possibly resulting from the anthraquinones.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] Since 2016, aloe vera whole leaf extract is classified as a possible human carcinogen (group 2B) by the International Agency for Research on Cancer.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] Use of aloe vera on the skin is generally not associated with significant side effects.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] Oral ingestion of aloe vera is potentially toxic, and may cause abdominal cramps and diarrhea which in turn can decrease the absorption of drugs.
[src:ais-kacang/aloe-vera] Ingested aloe products may have adverse interactions with prescription drugs, such as those used to treat blood clots, diabetes, heart disease and potassium-lowering agents (such as Digoxin), and diuretics, among others.
